annotation.value: In the FileContext module, specify parameters to construct a file name of the form <rundir>/<runday>_<var>.6? In the Scan module, specify which gridfield you want to read: "H" for horizontal grid, "V" for vertical grid, "T" for timestep grid, or "D" for singleton grid storing constants.
Use the apply operator to calculate a z
Use the Apply operator to calculate a new attribute. In this case, we calculate a new depth to improve the color range.
Use the Accumulate operator to assign numeric ids to the nodes, which will be used in downstream processing. We assign Ids to both the horizontal gridfield H and the vertical gridfield V.
Visualize the vertial gridfield V, a simple linear gridfield.
Use the Restrict operator to reduce the grid to those cells within a bounding box containing the mouth of the river. Coordinates are Oregon State Plane, WSG84 (in meters)

The GridFieldToVTK module lets you specify which attribute will be the active scalars. The only attributes associated with the horizontal grid are x, y, h, and b. h is the depth in meters below mean sea level (downward positive). b is the integer index of the bottom-most node. (Except in one version of the file format, where b is the bottom depth in meters.) Note that the vertical grid is oriented directly at the viewer, so you must revolve the image to see it.
Construct a 3D grid using the Cross operator with arguments H and V.
Use the Cross operator to construct a 3D grid. Also use another Apply operator in order to scale up the the vertical dimension to make it visible.
This recipe is equivalent to "Restrict Then Cross", but is slower since it must construct the entire 3D grid before reducing it to the area around the mouth.

annotation.value: Use the Bind operator to read in the surface information at a particular timestep. The surface attribute tells which position in the vertical represents the boundary between wet and dry nodes. To use the Bind operator, you specify the variable to read (the catalog must be aware of the variable) the name it should have in the gridfield (attribute), and the attribute to use as position information (hpos, in this case). The surf attribute is an attribute of the horizontal gridfield.

Use the bind operator to read in the surface information (as in Show Dry Nodes) as well as salinity information. Due to the way the file format is organized, we have to compute offsets for each value, store these in an attribute, then pass this attribute to the bind operator. The final visualization here does not look very good, since the "dry" nodes are included with their invalid values of -99.
Use the restrict operator to remove dry nodes.
Use more bind operators to bind more attributes. Here, we bind "u", "v", and "salt"

Here we use multiple bind operators to bind multiple attributes. We bind "u", "v" and "salt", then use these attributes to calculate the salt flux. We assign "u,v" to be the vectors of the VTK dataset, and "saltflux" to be the scalars. Change the timestep of the timestep context to see a different image.
Use python source to involve the cardinality of the vertical grid in a calucation on the horizontal grid.

Remove the surface attribute so that we can do a fast parameter exploration over timesteps. With caching, the expensive cross product does not need to be recomputed at each step. Note: During a parameter exploration on tstep of the TimeContext module, the cross product operator still seems to fire, suggesting that caching is not behaving as I expect.
Adjust z by the bathymetry. This change is a candidate for automatic application to a different branch.
